{"title_page": "Catty", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Stack|[[Image:Sam-ho-chhi.jpg|thumb|left|Fruit sold in catties (\u65a4) in a market in [[Sanchong]], [[New Taipei]], Taiwan.]]|[[File:Lin Hua Tai tea pricelist.jpg|thumb|left|Tea priced by the catty in [[Dadaocheng]], [[Taipei]], Taiwan.]]|float=left}}\n\n[[File:Hong kong weight standards 2.jpg|thumb|A spring scale in Hong Kong shows conversions between [[metric system|<span style=\"color:red\">metric system</span>]], [[Chinese_units_of_measurement|<span style=\"color:#22B14C\">traditional Chinese unit</span>]] and [[British Imperial Units|<span style=\"color:#0000FF\">British Imperial Units</span>]]. ]]\n{{Chinese|c=\u65a4|p=j\u012bn|w=chin|y=g\u00e0n|poj=kin, kun|kanji=\u65a4|hiragana=\u304d\u3093|romaji=kin|hangul=\uadfc|hanja=\u65a4|rr=geun|vie=c\u00e2n|ind=kati|msa=kati}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| bgcolor      = \n| name         = Catty\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| standard     = [[Chinese_units_of_measurement|traditional Chinese unit]]\n| quantity     = [[mass]]\n| symbol       = {{linktext|\u65a4}}\n| symbol2      = \n| namedafter   = \n| extralabel   = \n| extradata    = \n| units1       = Chinese unit\n| inunits1     = 16 [[tael|\u5169]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;10 [[tael|\u4e24]] (in Mainland China)\n| units2       = [[China]]\n| inunits2     = 500 [[gram|g]]\n| units3       = [[Japan]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Taiwan]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Thailand]]\n| inunits3     = <br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;600 [[gram|g]]\n| units4       = [[Hong Kong]]\n| inunits4     = 604.78982 [[gram|g]]\n| units5       = [[Malaysia]]\n| inunits5     = 604.79 [[gram|g]]\n| units6       = [[Singapore]]\n| inunits6     = 604.8 [[gram|g]]\n| units_imp1   = [[Hong Kong]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Malaysia]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Singapore]]\n| inunits_imp1 = <br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{sfrac|1|1|3}} [[Pound (mass)|lb]]\n<!--...-->\n| units_imp6   = \n| inunits_imp6 = \n| units_us1    = \n| inunits_us1  = \n<!--...-->\n| units_us6    = \n| inunits_us6  = \n}}\n\nThe '''catty''', '''kati''' or '''jin''' (commonly in China), symbol '''\u65a4''', is a traditional Chinese unit of [[mass]] used across [[East Asia|East]] and Southeast Asia, notably for weighing food and other groceries in some [[Wet market|wet markets]], [[street markets]], and shops.  Related units include the [[picul]], equal to 100 catties, and the [[tael]] (also spelled ''tahil'', in [[Malay language|Malay]]/[[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]), which is {{frac|16}} of a catty.  A [[stone (Chinese mass)|stone]] is a former unit used in Hong Kong equal to 120 catties and a ''gwan'' (\u921e) is 30 catties.  Catty or ''kati'' is still used in South East Asia as a unit of measurement in some contexts especially by the significant [[Overseas Chinese]] populations of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore.\n\nThe catty is traditionally equivalent to around 1\u2153 [[pound avoirdupois]], formalised as 604.78982 [[gram]]s in Hong Kong,<ref name = \"hk_law\">{{cite web|title = Weights and Measures Ordinance |work = The Law of Hong Kong | url = https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap68!en@1997-06-30T00:00:00?keyword.PIT_DATE=&keyword.WITHIN_ALL=&keyword.LEG_TYPE=3&keyword.LEG_TYPE=1&keyword.LEG_TYPE=2&keyword.NEAR_PHRASE=&keyword.PART_NO=&keyword.NEAR_IN_ORDER=&keyword.WITHIN_TEXT=Y&keyword.SEARCH_KEYWORD=units&keyword.NEAR_DIST=&keyword.ANY_WORDS=&ADVANCED_SEARCH_FLAG=&keyword.ENABLE_WORD_STEMMING=&keyword.SCHEDULE_APPENDIX_ANNEX_NO=&SEARCH_OPTION=K&keyword.EXACT_PHRASE=&keyword.SUBDIVISION_NO=&keyword.SEARCH_MODE=P&keyword.WITHIN_TAGS=&keyword.NO_WORDS=&keyword.SEARCH_FIELD=E&keyword.ALL_WORDS=&keyword.PIT_TIME=&keyword.CASE_SENSITIVE=&keyword.ADVANCED_SEARCH=&keyword.CHAPTER_TITLE=&keyword.SECTION_RULE_NO=&REFINED_SEARCH=&keyword.CHAPTER_NO=&keyword.DIVISION_NO=&crossReference.EX_CHAPTER_NO=&keyword.PIT_TYPE=C&keyword.BILINGUAL=}}</ref> 604.79&nbsp;grams in Malaysia<ref name=\"my_law\">{{cite web|title=Weights and Measures Act 1972 |work=Laws of Malaysia |url=http://www.kpdnkk.gov.my/akta-timbang-dan-sukat-1972 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201182503/http://www.kpdnkk.gov.my/akta-timbang-dan-sukat-1972 |archivedate=2014-02-01 }}</ref> and 604.8 grams in Singapore.<ref name = \"sg_law\">{{cite web|title = Weights and Measures Act | url = http://statutes.agc.gov.sg/non_version/cgi-bin/cgi_retrieve.pl?&actno=Reved-349&date=latest&method=p}}</ref> In some countries, the weight has been rounded to 600&nbsp;grams (Taiwan<ref>[http://www.gio.gov.tw/taiwan-website/5-gp/yearbook/2001/appendix6.htm Weights and Measures in Use in Taiwan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229224604/http://www.gio.gov.tw/taiwan-website/5-gp/yearbook/2001/appendix6.htm# |date=2010-12-29 }} from the ''Republic of China Yearbook'' \u2013 Taiwan 2001.</ref>, Japan, Korea<ref>[https://www.mfds.go.kr/eng/eng/download.do;jsessionid=FooH3taRfU3x5etkddZGD12OQSgkSRs8P3a9LjjW29D1vmaV9cFcs50iIxHiHG3y?boardCode=17840&boardSeq=70932&fileSeq=2 Regulation on Approval and Notification of Herbal (crude)Medicinal Preparations, Etc.]</ref> and Thailand). In [[mainland China]], the catty (more commonly translated as jin within China) has been rounded to 500&nbsp;grams and is referred to as the '''market catty''' (\u5e02\u65a4 ''sh\u00ecj\u012bn'') in order to distinguish it from the \"metric catty\" (\u516c\u65a4 ''g\u014dngj\u012bn''), or kilogram, and it is subdivided into 10 taels rather than the usual 16.\n\n{{clr}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chinese units of measurement]]\n*[[Taiwanese units of measurement]]\n*[[Japanese units of measurement]]\n*[[Caddy (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Tea caddy]]\n\n[[Category:Units of mass]]\n[[Category:Chinese units in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Stack|[[Image:Sam-ho-chhi.jpg|thumb|left|Fruit sold in catties (\u65a4) in a market in [[Sanchong]], [[New Taipei]], Taiwan.]]|[[File:Lin Hua Tai tea pricelist.jpg|thumb|left|Tea priced by the catty in [[Dadaocheng]], [[Taipei]], Taiwan.]]|float=left}}\n\n[[File:Hong kong weight standards 2.jpg|thumb|A spring scale in Hong Kong shows conversions between [[metric system|<span style=\"color:red\">metric system</span>]], [[Chinese_units_of_measurement|<span style=\"color:#22B14C\">traditional Chinese unit</span>]] and [[British Imperial Units|<span style=\"color:#0000FF\">British Imperial Units</span>]]. ]]\n{{Chinese|c=\u65a4|p=j\u012bn|w=chin|y=g\u00e0n|poj=kin, kun|kanji=\u65a4|hiragana=\u304d\u3093|romaji=kin|hangul=\uadfc|hanja=\u65a4|rr=geun|vie=c\u00e2n|ind=kati|msa=kati}}\n{{Infobox unit\n| bgcolor      = \n| name         = Catty\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| standard     = [[Chinese_units_of_measurement|traditional Chinese unit]]\n| quantity     = [[mass]]\n| symbol       = {{linktext|\u65a4}}\n| symbol2      = \n| namedafter   = \n| extralabel   = \n| extradata    = \n| units1       = Chinese unit\n| inunits1     = 16 [[tael|\u5169]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;10 [[tael|\u4e24]] (in Mainland China)\n| units2       = [[China]]\n| inunits2     = 500 [[gram|g]]\n| units3       = [[Japan]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Taiwan]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Thailand]]\n| inunits3     = <br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;600 [[gram|g]]\n| units4       = [[Hong Kong]]\n| inunits4     = 604.78982 [[gram|g]]\n| units5       = [[Malaysia]]\n| inunits5     = 604.79 [[gram|g]]\n| units6       = [[Singapore]]\n| inunits6     = 604.8 [[gram|g]]\n| units_imp1   = [[Hong Kong]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Malaysia]]<br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[[Singapore]]\n| inunits_imp1 = <br /><!--\n-->&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{{sfrac|1|1|3}} [[Pound (mass)|lb]]\n<!--...-->\n| units_imp6   = \n| inunits_imp6 = \n| units_us1    = \n| inunits_us1  = \n<!--...-->\n| units_us6    = \n| inunits_us6  = \n}}\n\nThe '''catty''', '''kati''' or '''jin''' (commonly in China) , symbol '''\u65a4''', is a traditional Chinese unit of [[mass]] used across [[East Asia|East]] and Southeast Asia, notably for weighing food and other groceries in some [[Wet market|wet markets]], [[street markets]], and shops.  Related units include the [[picul]], equal to 100 catties, and the [[tael]] (also spelled ''tahil'', in [[Malay language|Malay]]/[[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]), which is {{frac|16}} of a catty.  A [[stone (Chinese mass)|stone]] is a former unit used in Hong Kong equal to 120 catties and a ''gwan'' (\u921e) is 30 catties.  Catty or ''kati'' is still used in South East Asia as a unit of measurement in some contexts especially by the significant [[Overseas Chinese]] populations of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, and Singapore.\n\nThe catty is traditionally equivalent to around 1\u2153 [[pound avoirdupois]], formalised as 604.78982 [[gram]]s in Hong Kong,<ref name = \"hk_law\">{{cite web|title = Weights and Measures Ordinance |work = The Law of Hong Kong | url = https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap68!en@1997-06-30T00:00:00?keyword.PIT_DATE=&keyword.WITHIN_ALL=&keyword.LEG_TYPE=3&keyword.LEG_TYPE=1&keyword.LEG_TYPE=2&keyword.NEAR_PHRASE=&keyword.PART_NO=&keyword.NEAR_IN_ORDER=&keyword.WITHIN_TEXT=Y&keyword.SEARCH_KEYWORD=units&keyword.NEAR_DIST=&keyword.ANY_WORDS=&ADVANCED_SEARCH_FLAG=&keyword.ENABLE_WORD_STEMMING=&keyword.SCHEDULE_APPENDIX_ANNEX_NO=&SEARCH_OPTION=K&keyword.EXACT_PHRASE=&keyword.SUBDIVISION_NO=&keyword.SEARCH_MODE=P&keyword.WITHIN_TAGS=&keyword.NO_WORDS=&keyword.SEARCH_FIELD=E&keyword.ALL_WORDS=&keyword.PIT_TIME=&keyword.CASE_SENSITIVE=&keyword.ADVANCED_SEARCH=&keyword.CHAPTER_TITLE=&keyword.SECTION_RULE_NO=&REFINED_SEARCH=&keyword.CHAPTER_NO=&keyword.DIVISION_NO=&crossReference.EX_CHAPTER_NO=&keyword.PIT_TYPE=C&keyword.BILINGUAL=}}</ref> 604.79&nbsp;grams in Malaysia<ref name=\"my_law\">{{cite web|title=Weights and Measures Act 1972 |work=Laws of Malaysia |url=http://www.kpdnkk.gov.my/akta-timbang-dan-sukat-1972 |url-status=dead |